\begin_layout Standard
As a recent development of the liquid state theory, the 3D RISM provides
 a discrete description of the solvent around the solute, using solute-solvent
 correlation functions as fundamental variables.
 The relevant theory has been thoroughly discussed 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "Sato13,Kovalenko99a,Kovalenko00b,book:Hirata03"

\end_inset

.
 Therefore we sketch here only the fundamental formulae of the solute-solvent
 3D RISM integral equation, in the form of a convolution 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:Hirata03"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
h^{uv}=c^{uv}\ast\chi^{v}.\label{eq:rism-uv}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $h^{uv}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c^{uv}$
\end_inset

 are (rectangular) matrices of the 3D total correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\alpha}^{uv}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 and 3D direct correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\alpha}^{uv}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

, both unknowns of the equation.
 The superscripts 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 label the solute and the solvent, respectively.
 The subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 enumerate the solvent site interacting with the whole solute.
 In Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rism-uv"

\end_inset

, the solvent is represented by its (square symmetric) susceptibility matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{v}=\omega^{v}+\rho h^{vv}$
\end_inset

 which can be obtained self-consistently from the pure solvent RISM equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "book:Hirata03,Kovalenko99b"

\end_inset

; in practice one operates with the dimensionless Fourier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\chi}^{v}(k)$
\end_inset

 of the solvent susceptibility.
 The low 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\chi}_{\alpha\gamma}^{v}(0)=\rho\kappa/\beta$
\end_inset

 encodes the solvent compressibility 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 and the next leading 
\begin_inset Formula $o(k^{2})$
\end_inset

 
\color blue
term
\color inherit
 is calibrated by the dielectric response of the solvent 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Perkyns92"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1/T$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of the temperature 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to the 1D RISM, a closure relation is needed to render Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rism-uv"

\end_inset

 solvable.
 In all RISM calculations we use the closure proposed by Kovalenko and Hirata
 (KH) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kovalenko99a"

\end_inset

: 
\color blue

\begin_inset Formula $h_{\alpha}=f(-\beta u_{\alpha}+h_{\alpha}-c_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

)
\color inherit
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=\exp(x)-1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\le0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=x$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 Here 
\color blue

\begin_inset Formula $u_{\alpha}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 
\color inherit
is the interaction potential between solvent site 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and the solute.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The excess chemical potential of solvation is given by the distribution
 functions.
 For the KH closure, it has the analytical form 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "book:Hirata03,Kovalenko99a"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color blue
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mu=\frac{\rho}{\beta}\int\sum_{\alpha=1}^{N_{\text{v}}}\left[\Theta(-h_{\alpha})h_{\alpha}^{2}/2-c_{\alpha}-c_{\alpha}h_{\alpha}/2\right]d^{3}r\label{eq:mu}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\color inherit
Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta(x)$
\end_inset

 is the Heaviside step function which ensures that the terms 
\begin_inset Formula $h^{2}$
\end_inset

 contribute only in the depletion regions,
\color blue
 
\begin_inset Formula $h_{\alpha}<0$
\end_inset


\color inherit
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Kovalenko99a"

\end_inset

.
 This expression, together with a linear convolution relation, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:rism-uv"

\end_inset

, between the total and direct correlation functions 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

