Comparing approximate methods we found that representing the solute charge
 density by point charges of a force field or by the gas-phase QM electron
 density leads to quite comparable solvation energies with a mean absolute
 deviations of ~1
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

kcal/mol from each other and 1.4--1.6
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

kcal/mol from experiment.
 We also examined an approximate way to estimate the electron relaxation
 caused by the solvent reaction field and the resulting solvent relaxation
 energy.
 This approximate approach and the fully self-consistent 3D RISM QM method
 agree on average to better than 0.4
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

kcal/mol.
 The ratio of the solute polarization and the solvent relaxation energies
 is nearly constant for all solutes studied; the value of this ratio differs
 notably from the linear-response electrostatic limit of 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

