\begin_layout Standard
Relaxation terms have been suggested to be important for neutral molecules
 with overall rather small solvation energies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sato13,Sato07a"

\end_inset

.
 The size of the relaxation terms determined here seems to support this
 argument.
 Nevertheless, the approximate PT2 method of second order for addressing
 relaxation terms only slightly improves the comparison to experiment, while
 a self-consistent approach hardly improves it.
 This latter finding may be due to an artificial polarization of the electron
 density by nearby localized positive volume charges of the solvent medium.
 That effect likely is overestimated in the absence of repulsive exchange
 interactions between solute and solvent electrons.
 It may be indicative for this artifact that the induced solute dipole moments
 are slightly overestimated in comparison to the PCM approach.
 An increased water hydrogen and oxygen density around the solute in the
 SCF-RISM also supports this hypothesis.
 Another possibility is that an asymptotic correction limited to a term
 strictly proportional to the solute volume does not suffice for reducing
 the intrinsic error of 3D RISM to better than 1--2
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

kcal/mol for neutral solutes in water.
 A careful analysis of the asymptotic behavior of 3D RISM may offer a more
 accurate error estimate and resolve some of remaining issues.
 
