\begin_layout Standard
For simplicity, assume a model that is characterized by a single degree
 of freedom 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, e.g.
\begin_inset space \thinspace{}
\end_inset

the dipole moment.
 Minimization of an energy expression, for 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e[d]=a(d-d_{0})^{2}/2,
\]

\end_inset

leads to a “permanent” dipole moment 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The response to an additional electric field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta e=-fd$
\end_inset

, results in 
\begin_inset Formula $d-d_{0}=a^{-1}f$
\end_inset

 and suggests to identify 
\begin_inset Formula $a^{-1}$
\end_inset

 with the “polarizability” of the system.
 Using a simple expression for the solvation energy of a rigid dipole, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu[d]=-b(d-d_{\ast})^{2}/2,
\]

\end_inset

is sufficiently flexible for parametrizing the electric cavity reaction
 field 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\ast}[d]=-\partial\mu/\partial d$
\end_inset

 to have a linear form with some, in general, non-zero intercept 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\ast}[0]=-bd_{\ast}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that embedding a frozen system 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}$
\end_inset

 in the “gas phase” into a solvent would lead to the solvation energy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu[d_{0}]=-b(d_{0}-d_{\ast})^{2}/2.
\]

\end_inset

By minimizing the sum 
\begin_inset Formula $G[d]=e[d]+\mu[d]$
\end_inset

, one finds a new minimum at
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{1}=\frac{ad_{0}-bd_{\ast}}{a-b},
\]

\end_inset

 assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $0<b<a$
\end_inset

.
 Finally one obtains the energy 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e[d_{1}]=\frac{a}{2}\left[\frac{b}{a-b}\right]^{2}(d_{0}-d_{\ast})^{2},
\]

\end_inset

 the “solvation” energy 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu[d_{1}]=-\frac{b}{2}\left[\frac{a}{a-b}\right]^{2}(d_{0}-d_{\ast})^{2},
\]

\end_inset

 and the total free energy
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G[d_{1}]=-\frac{ab}{2(a-b)}(d_{0}-d_{\ast})^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $0<b<a$
\end_inset

, the ratio of the changes
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\mu[d_{1}]-\mu[d_{0}]}{e[d_{1}]-e[d_{0}]}=-\left[2-\frac{b}{a}\right]
\]

\end_inset

has a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

, independent of the system parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\ast}$
\end_inset

.
 Naturally only the ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

, defining the scale of the two contributions, matters for this result.
 The relaxation effect of the free energy, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G[d_{1}]-G[d_{0}]=-\frac{b^{2}}{2(a-b)}(d_{0}-d_{\ast})^{2}
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(b^{2})$
\end_inset

, compared to the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{O}(b)$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $G[d_{0}]$
\end_inset

.
 The limit 
\begin_inset Formula $b\to0$
\end_inset

 has to be carried out with care, for instance, by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\epsilon$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{\ast}=-f_{\ast}/\epsilon$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $bd_{\ast}=-f_{\ast}=\text{const}$
\end_inset

.
 By discarding divergent terms, independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu[d]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G[d]$
\end_inset

, one obtains
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
G[d_{1}]-G[d_{0}]\to\frac{f_{\ast}^{2}}{2a}
\]

\end_inset

and the above ratio of the two contributions to this form of the relaxation
 energy is exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

